DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260402
RRULE:FREQ=YEARLY
SUMMARY:🌾 Scotch Broom (flowers/shoots)  Apr–May
DESCRIPTION:SEASON: Apr → May\nPEAK:   Mar · Jun\n\nSpecies:    Cytisus 
 scoparius\nDifficulty: Hard/Expert\nHabitat:    Roadsides\, open disturbed
  areas\, coastal scrub\nRegions:    Sonoma · Mendocino · Marin · Santac
 ruz · Foothills\n\nInvasive broom blanketing Northern California hillside
 s in spring yellow. Very young unopened flower buds are edible as a caper 
 substitute — the rest of the plant is toxic.\n\n⚠ Lookalike: Similar b
 room species vary in edibility. Entire plant is toxic EXCEPT very young fl
 ower buds and shoots. Use extreme caution. Never eat leaves\, seeds\, or m
 ature plant.\n\n💡 Tip: CAUTION: Only the very young flower buds before 
 opening are edible\, pickled like capers. Rest of plant is toxic. Harvesti
 ng it is an ecological service — it's highly invasive.\n\n— Cedar · N
 orthern California Foraging
CATEGORIES:INVASIVES
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
