DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260202
RRULE:FREQ=YEARLY
SUMMARY:🌾 Yellow Starthistle (young rosette)  Feb–Apr
DESCRIPTION:SEASON: Feb → Apr\nPEAK:   Jan · May\n\nSpecies:    Centaure
 a solstitialis\nDifficulty: Hard/Expert\nHabitat:    Dry roadsides\, overg
 razed hillsides\, disturbed fields\nRegions:    Napa · Lake · East · Fo
 othills · Sonoma\n\nThe most invasive weed in California (15+ million acr
 es infested). Young first-year rosette leaves edible before spines develop
  — similar to artichoke in flavor. Harvesting it is a genuine ecological
  service.\n\n⚠ Lookalike: Mature plant has viciously sharp spines — on
 ly young pre-spine rosettes are safe to handle.\n\n💡 Tip: ONLY harvest 
 the low flat first-year rosette in winter/early spring before flower stalk
  emerges. Once spines appear\, do not touch. Young leaves blanched are mil
 d and slightly artichoke-flavored.\n\n— Cedar · Northern California For
 aging
CATEGORIES:INVASIVES
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
